Mathematical Transformation

End Goal is to make the data Normal
i.e. Probability Distribution Function should be Normal

Statistical Model performs well in Normal Data (Linear Regression, Logistic Regression)

A. Function Transformation

  1. Logarithmic Transformation (Use in Right Skewed data)
  2. Square Transformation (Use in Left Skewed data)
  3. Reciprocal Transformation
  4. Square Root Transformation

B. Power Transformation

  1. Exponential Transformation
  2. Box Cox Transformation
  3. Yeo-Johnson

*** ***

import scipy.stats as stat
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

#### Q-Q plot
def plot_data(df,feature):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    df[feature].hist()
    plt.title("PDF Plot")
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    stat.probplot(df[feature],dist='norm',plot=plt)
    plt.title("Q-Q Plot")
    plt.show()

Function Transform

from sklearn.preprocessing import FunctionTransformer
trf = FunctionTransformer(func=np.log1p)
X_train_transformed = trf.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_transformed = trf.transform(X_test)

Power Transform

from sklearn.preprocessing import PowerTransformer
pt = PowerTransformer(method='box-cox')
X_train_transformed = pt.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_transformed = pt.transform(X_test)
pt.lambdas_.   #provide the value of lambda for each columns 

from sklearn.preprocessing import PowerTransformer
pt = PowerTransformer(method='box-cox')
X_train_transformed = pt.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_transformed = pt.transform(X_test)
pt.lambdas_.   #provide the value of lambda for each columns

  • Not applicable to data less than or equal to Zero
  • here we find optimal value of lambda by using
    • Maximum LikeliHood
    • Bayesian
